<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Further_reading">Further reading</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Congregational_church&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Further reading">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Works by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Waddington_(cleric)" title="John Waddington (cleric)">John Waddington</a>
<ul>
<li><i>Congregational Martyrs</i>. London, 1861, intended to form part of a series of 'Historical Papers,' which, however, were not continued; 2nd ed. 1861</li>
<li><i>Congregational Church History from the Reformation to 1662</i>, London, 1862, awarded the bicentenary prize offered by the Congregational Union</li>
<li><i>Surrey Congregational History</i>, London, 1866, in which he dealt more particularly with the records of his own congregation.</li>
<li><i>Congregational History</i>, 5 vols., London, 1869–1880</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&amp;d=5002019127">McConnell, Michael W. "Establishment and Disestablishment at the Founding, Part I: Establishment of Religion" <i>William and Mary Law Review</i>, Vol. 44, 2003, pp. 2105+</a></li>
</ul>
